    <h1>Prompt and wait</h1>
    <p>I think work is about to become two words. Prompt, and wait.</p>

    <p>Here is what I mean. Today, if you want something made, a person has to make it. You describe it, they do it, you wait on a human. Soon you describe it and a system does it. Not a chatbot answering a question. A goal, handed to agents that break it down, call other agents, and keep going until the thing is actually done.</p>

    <p>Say I want a burger. An agent checks the kitchen. No patties. So it spins up a second agent to get beef. That one has no cattle, so it calls a fleet to raise some. The patties come back, the first agent assembles the burger, something delivers it. At the end you have a burger, and all you did was wait.</p>

    <p>That is not science fiction. It is the thing we already have, pointed at a longer horizon and given the ability to call itself. The loop is the whole trick: keep going until the goal is met.</p>

    <p>The interesting part is what this does to scarcity. If any goal can be filled at close to zero cost and the only input left is patience, then scarcity of stuff is basically solved. That is abundance, on the supply side. The honest catch is who owns the fleets. Making things free is a technology problem. Sharing them is not. That part is politics, and it does not solve itself.</p>

    <p>And here is the part that matters for you and me. When production gets cheap, the scarce thing moves. It always moves. Solve making, and the bottleneck jumps to time, or attention, or knowing what to even ask for. So the skill that survives every version of this is the same one: find the thing actually holding the goal back, and move it. Sometimes that is code. Sometimes it is a price. Sometimes it is that nobody knows you exist.</p>

    <p>Right now, for me, it is the last one. So I am writing this.</p>
  </main>

